Here is an example of how you can create a Discord bot using Discord.js v14 that can ban users from a server. This example assumes you have already set up a Discord application and obtained the token and client ID.

First, install the required package:

```bash
npm install discord.js
```

Then, create a file named `index.js` and add the following code:

```javascript
const { Client, Intents } = require('discord.js');
const { token, clientId } = require('./config.json');

// Create a new client instance
const client = new Client({
  intents: [
    Intents.FLAGS.Guilds,
    Intents.FLAGS.GuildMessages,
    Intents.FLAGS.MessageContent,
    Intents.FLAGS.MessageReaction,
    Intents.FLAGS.User
  ]
});

client.once('ready', () => {
  console.log('Ready!');
});

client.on('interactionCreate', async interaction => {
  if (!interaction.isCommand()) return;

  if (interaction.commandName === 'ban') {
    if (!interaction.member.permissions.has('BAN_MEMBERS')) {
      return interaction.reply('You do not have the permission to ban members.');
    }

    if (interaction.options.get('user') === null) {
      return interaction.reply('Please specify a valid user to ban.');
    }

    const user = interaction.options.get('user').user;
    const reason = interaction.options.get('reason')?.value;

    try {
      await interaction.guild.members.ban(user, { reason: reason || 'No reason provided' });
      return interaction.reply(`Successfully banned ${user.tag} for ${reason || 'No reason provided'}.`);
    } catch (error) {
      return interaction.reply('An error occurred while trying to ban the user.');
    }
  }
});

client.login(token);
```

Next, create a `config.json` file in the same directory as `index.js` and add your token and client ID:

```json
{
  "token": "YOUR_BOT_TOKEN",
  "clientId": "YOUR_CLIENT_ID"
}
```

Replace `YOUR_BOT_TOKEN` and `YOUR_CLIENT_ID` with your actual token and client ID.

Finally, run your bot using Node.js:

```bash
node index.js
```

Now, your Discord bot is ready to use. It will listen for slash commands and respond accordingly. When the `/ban` command is used, it will check if the user has the necessary permissions to ban members. If the user is valid, it will ban the specified user and provide a response. If there's an error during the banning process, it will notify the user.

Remember to set up the bot in your Discord server and enable the `BAN_MEMBERS` permission for the bot role. Also, make sure to create a new application on the Discord Developer Portal, obtain the token and client ID, and set up the bot in your server to use slash commands.

