```

The expected output for the given example would be:

```html
This is a <strong>bold</strong> text. It is also <em>italic</em>. Here's a <a href="https://example.com">link</a>.
```

To solve this problem, you can use regular expressions to match and replace the markdown syntax with corresponding HTML tags. Here's a possible implementation:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <regex>

std::string convertMarkdownToHTML(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html;

    // Bold syntax: **text**
    std::regex boldRegex("\\*\\*(.*?)\\*\\*");
    html = std::regex_replace(markdown, boldRegex, "<strong>$1</strong>");

    // Italic syntax: _text_
    std::regex italicRegex("\\_(.*?)\\_");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, italicRegex, "<em>$1</em>");

    // Link syntax: [text](url)
    std::regex linkRegex("\\[(.*?)\\]\\((.*?)\\)");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, linkRegex, "<a href=\"$2\">$1</a>");

    return html;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown = "This is a **bold** text. It is also _italic_. Here's a [link](https://example.com).";
    std::string html = convertMarkdownToHTML(markdown);
    std::cout << html << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

This implementation uses `std::regex_replace` to replace the matched markdown syntax with the corresponding HTML tags. The regular expressions are defined to match the specific syntax patterns for bold, italic, and links. The captured groups in the regular expressions are used to extract the text and URL for the link syntax.

When you run this code, it will output the expected HTML formatted text:

```html
This is a <strong>bold</strong> text. It is also <em>italic</em>. Here's a <a href="https://example.com">link</a>.
```

